🎯 Step 1 — Add the Gem
Gemfile
gem 'will_paginate', '~> 3.3'

Then:

bundle install

👉 Explain in interview:

We use will_paginate because Rails does not provide built-in pagination helpers. This gem adds pagination methods to ActiveRecord.

🎯 Step 2 — Add Pagination in Controller

Suppose we have a UsersController.

Before Pagination
def index
  @users = User.all
end

⚠️ Problem: Loads all users → bad for performance.

After Pagination
def index
  @users = User.paginate(page: params[:page], per_page: 10)
end
Explain This Clearly:

page: params[:page] → Current page number from URL

per_page: 10 → 10 records per page

URL becomes:

/users?page=2

Internally SQL becomes:

SELECT * FROM users LIMIT 10 OFFSET 10;

Because:

OFFSET = (page - 1) * per_page
OFFSET = (2 - 1) * 10 = 10

💬 Interview line:

will_paginate internally uses LIMIT and OFFSET to fetch only required records from the database.

🎯 Step 3 — Add Pagination Links in View
app/views/users/index.html.erb
<% @users.each do |user| %>
  <p><%= user.name %></p>
<% end %>

<%= will_paginate @users %>

👉 This generates:

Previous button

Next button

Page numbers

Automatically.

🎯 Step 4 — Optional Styling (Bootstrap Example)

By default, links are plain.

If using Bootstrap:

gem 'bootstrap-will_paginate'

Then:

<%= will_paginate @users, renderer: BootstrapPagination::Rails %>
🎯 Step 5 — Order + Pagination (Important Interview Point)

Always combine with order:

@users = User.order(created_at: :desc)
             .paginate(page: params[:page], per_page: 10)

Explain:

Pagination without ordering can cause inconsistent results if records are inserted during browsing.

🔥 This is a strong senior-level point.

🎯 Step 6 — Pagination in API (JSON)

For API:

def index
  @users = User.paginate(page: params[:page], per_page: 10)

  render json: {
    users: @users,
    current_page: @users.current_page,
    total_pages: @users.total_pages,
    total_entries: @users.total_entries
  }
end

Explain:

will_paginate provides helper methods like current_page and total_pages for API responses.

🎯 Step 7 — Edge Case Handling
Default page fallback
page = params[:page] || 1
@users = User.paginate(page: page, per_page: 10)
Handle empty dataset
<% if @users.any? %>
  <%= will_paginate @users %>
<% else %>
  <p>No users found</p>
<% end %>
🎯 Step 8 — Performance Concern (Very Important)

If interviewer asks:

❓ What problem with OFFSET?

Large OFFSET (e.g. page 10,000) is slow because DB must scan skipped rows.

Solution:

Cursor-based pagination:

User.where("id > ?", last_id).limit(10)

Explain:

Offset-based pagination is good for UI. Cursor-based is better for large datasets and APIs.

🎤 Final 1-Minute Interview Explanation

You can say:

In Rails, I integrate pagination using will_paginate gem. After adding the gem and running bundle install, I use Model.paginate(page: params[:page], per_page: 10) in the controller. It internally generates SQL using LIMIT and OFFSET. In the view, I use will_paginate @collection to generate page navigation links. I usually combine it with ordering to ensure consistent results. For APIs, I return pagination metadata like current_page and total_pages.


